00:00:52.730 --> 00:00:56.240
So what is that theory?

00:00:56.240 --> 00:00:58.800
The theory is built
up as follows.

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:01.790
Given a continuous function f--

00:01:01.790 --> 00:01:04.550
so this is just a refresher
on the definitions

00:01:04.550 --> 00:01:06.800
I introduced last time--

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:12.740
a partition is just
points between--

00:01:12.740 --> 00:01:23.450
just breaking up the interval
from a to b into points,

00:01:23.450 --> 00:01:28.100
into little subintervals, with
the norm of this partition

00:01:28.100 --> 00:01:33.650
being the length of the
longest subinterval [INAUDIBLE]

00:01:33.650 --> 00:01:35.240
which we refer to as a tag.

00:01:35.240 --> 00:01:37.790
It's just a set
of points with one

00:01:37.790 --> 00:01:41.200
lying in each of
these subintervals--

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:46.180
so for me, let's take them
all to be the right endpoint

00:01:46.180 --> 00:01:56.090
of these intervals--

00:01:56.090 --> 00:01:59.810
and then associated to a
tagged partition, which

00:01:59.810 --> 00:02:04.040
is a pair, x and [? xe. ?]
We associated a Riemann sum,

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:07.363
which is f evaluated at
these points times the length

00:02:07.363 --> 00:02:08.030
of the interval.

00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:15.460
So if we draw the graph
of a function f and--

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:16.390
say, in this picture--

00:02:24.260 --> 00:02:30.680
this number this
Riemann sum would then

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:37.160
be equal to the area of
these three boxes here.

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:39.200
OK?

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:41.720
And so our theory of
Riemann integration,

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:45.110
or our theory of the area
underneath the curve,

00:02:45.110 --> 00:02:50.570
is built on the following
goal, which is to show that,

00:02:50.570 --> 00:02:53.990
as these partitions
get finer and finer,

00:02:53.990 --> 00:02:57.950
as the norm of these
partitions goes to 0,

00:02:57.950 --> 00:03:02.440
these Riemann sums should
converge to some number.

00:03:02.440 --> 00:03:05.830
And that number, which we call
the Riemann integral of f,

00:03:05.830 --> 00:03:10.570
we interpret as the area
underneath the graph of f.

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:12.760
So the first goal--

00:03:12.760 --> 00:03:15.490
the main goal, really,
to start off with--

00:03:15.490 --> 00:03:19.180
is to show that this
is a reasonable--

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:25.400
that this is actually true that,
these Riemann sums do, in fact,

00:03:25.400 --> 00:03:30.010
converge to some
number as they become

00:03:30.010 --> 00:03:34.370
finer and finer for a
given continuous function.

00:03:38.770 --> 00:03:40.980
So that is the
main theorem, which

00:03:40.980 --> 00:03:46.500
I think is going to be the
main thing that we prove today.

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:55.560
So theorem of the
Riemann integral,

00:03:55.560 --> 00:03:56.720
which is the following--

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:05.120
let f be a continuous
function from a b to r--

00:04:05.120 --> 00:04:07.010
which, remember,
this is the notation

00:04:07.010 --> 00:04:09.750
we used from last time.

00:04:09.750 --> 00:04:13.200
Let me move my
picture over here.

00:04:18.980 --> 00:04:28.360
Then there exists a
unique real number, which

00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:38.540
we denote as the usual
symbol, integral a b f

00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:45.730
of x dx with the
following property--

00:04:53.020 --> 00:05:13.400
for every sequence
of partitions xr cr,

00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:20.750
such that the norm of these
partitions is going to 0 as r

00:05:20.750 --> 00:05:24.320
goes to infinity-- so
these partitions are

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:28.760
getting finer and finer
if the norm is going to 0.

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:31.370
Remember, the norm is the length
of the longest subinterval

00:05:31.370 --> 00:05:33.500
I have.

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:36.080
So for all sequence
of partitions,

00:05:36.080 --> 00:05:41.310
with norms converging
to 0, we have

00:05:41.310 --> 00:05:44.880
that the limit of
the Riemann sums

00:05:44.880 --> 00:06:00.830
exists and equals
this number, which

00:06:00.830 --> 00:06:04.210
we refer to as the
Riemann integral of f.

00:06:04.210 --> 00:06:05.866
OK?

00:06:05.866 --> 00:06:08.120
So there's a lot to unpack here.

00:06:08.120 --> 00:06:12.970
First off, what this
number, integral from a b

00:06:12.970 --> 00:06:15.850
to f of x dx-- this
property that it has is,

00:06:15.850 --> 00:06:17.680
no matter what
sequence of partitions

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:21.310
you take, as long as they're
becoming finer and finer,

00:06:21.310 --> 00:06:24.940
this limit actually exist,
and it equals the same number.

00:06:24.940 --> 00:06:28.360
It equals this number,
integral a b f of x dx.

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:32.260
So I could take two different
sequences of partitions

00:06:32.260 --> 00:06:35.680
becoming finer and finer,
look at the Riemann sums,

00:06:35.680 --> 00:06:40.360
and those two sequences
of Riemann sums converge,

00:06:40.360 --> 00:06:43.630
and they converge
to the same number--

00:06:43.630 --> 00:06:45.765
again, which we denote
by integral a b f

00:06:45.765 --> 00:06:49.480
of x dx, the Riemann
integral of f.

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:52.150
And so it's this
number, which we

00:06:52.150 --> 00:06:57.340
interpret as the area
underneath the graph of f.

00:06:57.340 --> 00:06:57.840
OK?

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:05.915
All right, so our main goal for
today is to prove this theorem.

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:21.450
So first off, there's two
parts of the statement here.

00:07:21.450 --> 00:07:23.040
There exists a
unique real number,

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:26.550
which we denoted by
that with this property.

00:07:26.550 --> 00:07:28.680
Uniqueness is immediate.

00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:34.510
If I have two real
numbers, such that,

00:07:34.510 --> 00:07:37.810
for all sequence of partitions
with norm going to 0,

00:07:37.810 --> 00:07:39.640
the limit of the
Riemann sums equals

00:07:39.640 --> 00:07:44.830
that limit, well, limits
of sequences are unique,

00:07:44.830 --> 00:07:47.330
and therefore, those two
numbers have to be the same.

00:07:47.330 --> 00:07:48.580
So uniqueness is clear.

00:07:48.580 --> 00:07:51.850
It's really the existence
part that we have to prove,

00:07:51.850 --> 00:07:54.250
that there exists a
real number so that,

00:07:54.250 --> 00:07:57.700
no matter what sequence
of partitions we take,

00:07:57.700 --> 00:07:59.920
the corresponding Riemann
sums converges to 0--

00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:01.090
as long as they become--

00:08:01.090 --> 00:08:03.760
the partitions become
finer and finer.

00:08:03.760 --> 00:08:04.260
OK?

00:08:08.110 --> 00:08:08.610
OK.

00:08:11.700 --> 00:08:15.430
Now, we're not going to
prove this theorem just yet.

00:08:15.430 --> 00:08:19.540
We need some facts that
will be used in the proof,

00:08:19.540 --> 00:08:21.420
so we're going to
put off proving

00:08:21.420 --> 00:08:25.590
this theorem for a few
minutes and first prove

00:08:25.590 --> 00:08:27.120
some necessary facts.

00:08:27.120 --> 00:08:41.419
So let me first define a useful
metric or number associated

00:08:41.419 --> 00:08:44.510
to-- or function associated to
a continuous function called

00:08:44.510 --> 00:08:46.190
the modulus of continuity.

00:08:46.190 --> 00:09:00.520
So for f continuous
function and eta positive,

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:07.710
we define the modulus
continuity omega f of eta--

00:09:07.710 --> 00:09:15.060
this is equal to the supremum of
f of x minus f of y [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:15.060 --> 00:09:18.870
absolute value, such that the
absolute value of x minus y

00:09:18.870 --> 00:09:21.890
is less than or equal
to [? eta. ?] OK?

00:09:24.970 --> 00:09:28.720
So what does this modulus
of continuity measure?

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:35.700
It measures, given-- if I
take any two points less than

00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:40.800
or equal to eta in distance,
and I look f of x minus f of y

00:09:40.800 --> 00:09:43.710
in absolute value, and
take the sup over all that,

00:09:43.710 --> 00:09:48.480
that gives me the
modulus of continuity.

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:53.220
Now, for example, let's
do the simplest example

00:09:53.220 --> 00:09:58.860
possible, f of x
equals ax plus b.

00:10:03.260 --> 00:10:06.310
Then what do we get?

00:10:06.310 --> 00:10:09.460
f of x minus f of y--

00:10:09.460 --> 00:10:14.515
this is equal to
a times x minus y.

00:10:20.550 --> 00:10:27.540
So if x minus y is less
than or equal to eta,

00:10:27.540 --> 00:10:35.200
we get that f of x minus
f of y in absolute value

00:10:35.200 --> 00:10:36.910
is less than or equal to--

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:41.770
well, it's equal to
a times x minus y

00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:46.610
is less than or
equal to a times eta.

00:10:46.610 --> 00:10:49.000
Right?

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.950
And therefore, absolute
value of a times eta

00:10:52.950 --> 00:10:57.810
is an upper bound for this
set for this function.

00:10:57.810 --> 00:10:59.310
And it's also achieved.

00:10:59.310 --> 00:11:02.490
If I take absolute value
of x minus y equal to eta,

00:11:02.490 --> 00:11:05.190
then this will be equality.

00:11:05.190 --> 00:11:10.410
So what I'm saying is
that, for this example,

00:11:10.410 --> 00:11:15.630
for f equals ax plus b,
the modulus of continuity

00:11:15.630 --> 00:11:19.470
is equal to a absolute
value of a times eta.

00:11:22.490 --> 00:11:22.990
OK.

00:11:27.510 --> 00:11:31.620
Now, something to note here is
that, for this guy right here,

00:11:31.620 --> 00:11:35.955
as eta goes to 0, the modulus
of continuity goes to 0 as well.

00:11:38.720 --> 00:11:43.710
And this is not special
to this function.

00:11:43.710 --> 00:11:46.290
In fact, it's true for
all continuous functions.

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:51.050
So let me state the
theorem and then give you

00:11:51.050 --> 00:11:52.770
an interpretation of it.

00:11:52.770 --> 00:11:54.380
So let me call this theorem 1.

00:11:58.450 --> 00:12:04.150
So for all f continuous on the
closed and bounded interval

00:12:04.150 --> 00:12:15.940
in a, b, limit as eta goes to
0 of omega f of eta equals 0.

00:12:15.940 --> 00:12:16.440
OK.

00:12:24.270 --> 00:12:27.690
So let me make one
more comment here.

00:12:27.690 --> 00:12:29.712
Maybe this will also--

00:12:29.712 --> 00:12:31.170
just to connect to
something we did

00:12:31.170 --> 00:12:33.630
earlier, which
follows immediately

00:12:33.630 --> 00:12:43.880
from the definition of this
guy, that for all x and y,

00:12:43.880 --> 00:12:49.270
this is true.

00:12:49.270 --> 00:12:51.800
OK?

00:12:51.800 --> 00:12:54.170
And therefore, you
should think of,

00:12:54.170 --> 00:12:58.100
I'm trying to make this small,
then the modulus of continuity

00:12:58.100 --> 00:13:01.940
is something that controls
how close f of x and f of y

00:13:01.940 --> 00:13:02.640
are together.

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:06.260
So somehow continuity is
controlled by this function,

00:13:06.260 --> 00:13:08.600
the modulus of continuity.

00:13:08.600 --> 00:13:10.595
So if this goes to 0, then--

00:13:13.860 --> 00:13:16.110
as this goes to
0, this goes to 0,

00:13:16.110 --> 00:13:19.295
then somehow I'm saying
f of x and f of y

00:13:19.295 --> 00:13:20.295
are very close together.

00:13:23.040 --> 00:13:25.050
So again, the
modulus of continuity

00:13:25.050 --> 00:13:30.160
is a way of measuring
continuity of a function.

00:13:30.160 --> 00:13:31.410
That's one way to think of it.

00:13:37.530 --> 00:13:43.476
All right, so let's prove this.

00:13:43.476 --> 00:13:47.000
This is a limited statement,
and what we're going to do

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.090
is we'll just prove it
the old-fashioned way.

00:13:50.090 --> 00:13:51.650
Let epsilon be positive.

00:13:56.680 --> 00:13:58.390
What do we know
about functions which

00:13:58.390 --> 00:14:00.610
are continuous on a closed
and bounded interval?

00:14:00.610 --> 00:14:03.790
While, they're also
uniformly continuous.

00:14:03.790 --> 00:14:13.010
So since f is continuous on this
closed and bounded interval,

00:14:13.010 --> 00:14:18.310
f is uniformly continuous.

00:14:18.310 --> 00:14:26.740
This means that there
exists delta 0 positive,

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:35.580
such that, for all x and y,
x and y less than delta 0

00:14:35.580 --> 00:14:43.557
implies that f of x minus
f of y is less than--

00:14:43.557 --> 00:14:44.640
let me put epsilon over 2.

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:46.780
I'm going to give myself
a little space here.

00:14:46.780 --> 00:14:47.280
OK?

00:14:51.210 --> 00:14:54.570
So just to recall,
what we're trying

00:14:54.570 --> 00:14:57.450
to do here in terms of the
definition of what this means--

00:14:57.450 --> 00:15:00.930
we're trying to show that,
for all epsilon positive,

00:15:00.930 --> 00:15:09.965
there exists delta positive,
such that, for all eta--

00:15:12.660 --> 00:15:14.940
eta's actually a positive
number here, so--

00:15:17.930 --> 00:15:22.480
implies omega of eta
is less than epsilon.

00:15:22.480 --> 00:15:22.980
OK?

00:15:31.580 --> 00:15:32.080
OK.

00:15:35.794 --> 00:15:39.130
All right, so this is what
we're trying to prove.

00:15:39.130 --> 00:15:41.030
We know that, for a
continuous function,

00:15:41.030 --> 00:15:43.330
it's uniformly continuous,
and therefore, there exists

00:15:43.330 --> 00:15:47.410
is delta 0 so that, when x
minus y is less than delta 0,

00:15:47.410 --> 00:15:50.380
f of x minus f of y is less
than epsilon over 2 for all

00:15:50.380 --> 00:15:52.010
x, y in the interval.

00:15:52.010 --> 00:15:52.510
OK?

00:15:58.710 --> 00:16:01.170
So basically, I'm
going to choose delta

00:16:01.170 --> 00:16:08.568
to be this delta 0, the
delta I need for this.

00:16:08.568 --> 00:16:09.985
And now let me
show that it works.

00:16:13.050 --> 00:16:17.480
Suppose eta is less than delta,
which, remember, is delta 0.

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:23.990
Then, if x minus y
is less than eta--

00:16:23.990 --> 00:16:26.640
which, again, is less than--

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:29.420
less than or equal to eta,
which is less than delta 0--

00:16:29.420 --> 00:16:37.970
I get that f of x minus f of
y is less than epsilon over 2.

00:16:37.970 --> 00:16:41.390
Basically, I just rewrote
what I had right there.

00:16:41.390 --> 00:16:50.860
And therefore, this implies
that epsilon over 2 is an upper

00:16:50.860 --> 00:17:03.440
bound for the set f of x
minus f of y, x minus y,

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:09.380
which is less than eta, which
implies that the supremum

00:17:09.380 --> 00:17:11.510
of this set-- which
is, by definition--

00:17:18.760 --> 00:17:21.569
so I'm just going to
put brackets here,

00:17:21.569 --> 00:17:24.240
and I hope that's clear that
I'm referring to this set

00:17:24.240 --> 00:17:26.220
here when I put that here--

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:27.780
that the supremum
of this set has

00:17:27.780 --> 00:17:31.440
to be less than or equal
to this upper bound, which

00:17:31.440 --> 00:17:32.860
is less than epsilon.

00:17:32.860 --> 00:17:33.360
OK?

00:17:33.360 --> 00:17:38.530
So we've proven that, if
eta is less than delta,

00:17:38.530 --> 00:17:44.440
then the modulus of
continuity of f--

00:17:44.440 --> 00:17:46.760
of eta is less than epsilon.

00:17:46.760 --> 00:17:49.225
And therefore, this is
what we wanted to prove.

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:07.940
OK.

00:18:22.010 --> 00:18:28.810
All right, so that's
one fact that I need,

00:18:28.810 --> 00:18:31.420
that this modulus of
continuity-- which, remember,

00:18:31.420 --> 00:18:33.670
is the supremum of the
difference of f of x and f

00:18:33.670 --> 00:18:36.970
of y, as long as x and
y are bounded by eta--

00:18:36.970 --> 00:18:39.250
that this converges
to 0 as eta converges

00:18:39.250 --> 00:18:42.110
to 0 for all
continuous functions.

00:18:42.110 --> 00:18:42.610
OK?

00:18:42.610 --> 00:18:49.980
And this is key in showing that
the Riemann integral exists

00:18:49.980 --> 00:18:51.420
for continuous functions.

00:18:54.570 --> 00:18:56.880
So theorem two is the following.

00:18:56.880 --> 00:19:02.540
So this is going to
tell us how two Riemann

00:19:02.540 --> 00:19:06.860
sums are comparable
if one partition is

00:19:06.860 --> 00:19:08.640
finer than the other.

00:19:08.640 --> 00:19:28.480
So if I have two tagged
partitions of a, b,

00:19:28.480 --> 00:19:34.850
such that x prime
is a subset of x--

00:19:34.850 --> 00:19:37.800
so this means that x prime--

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:40.370
so this is a partition--
a breakup of a, b--

00:19:40.370 --> 00:19:44.160
that contains all the
points of x and more.

00:19:44.160 --> 00:19:44.660
OK?

00:19:44.660 --> 00:19:46.220
So it's a finer partition.

00:19:49.170 --> 00:19:54.700
And we refer to x prime as a
refinement of the partition x.

00:20:03.050 --> 00:20:05.480
All right, so we
have two partitions.

00:20:05.480 --> 00:20:10.340
One is finer than the other,
and a continuous function f.

00:20:10.340 --> 00:20:13.760
Then we can estimate the
difference in the Riemann sums.

00:20:21.660 --> 00:20:26.300
This is less than or equal
to the modulus of continuity

00:20:26.300 --> 00:20:33.770
of f evaluated at the
norm of the courser

00:20:33.770 --> 00:20:36.305
partition times the
length of the interval.

00:20:38.810 --> 00:20:39.310
OK?

00:20:50.860 --> 00:20:53.950
OK, so this says, as long as--

00:20:53.950 --> 00:21:00.820
one way to think about it is,
if the partition x is very fine,

00:21:00.820 --> 00:21:03.220
and then I take a finer
partition, that's not

00:21:03.220 --> 00:21:05.470
going to change the
Riemann sum too much,

00:21:05.470 --> 00:21:06.970
because remember,
this is converging

00:21:06.970 --> 00:21:10.710
to 0 as the norm of the
partition-- how fine it is,

00:21:10.710 --> 00:21:13.990
or you can think how coarse
it is-- is going to 0.

00:21:20.270 --> 00:21:22.350
OK, so the idea is very simple.

00:21:22.350 --> 00:21:25.220
It's just going to take me a
little bit just to write down.

00:21:34.730 --> 00:21:39.020
Like I said, this partition
being contained in the other

00:21:39.020 --> 00:21:45.170
means this partition has all the
points in x and then some more.

00:21:45.170 --> 00:21:48.770
We're going to break
these partitions up into--

00:21:48.770 --> 00:21:52.400
or at least this
one up into parts

00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:57.500
where it's points in x and
then plus the extra one.

00:21:57.500 --> 00:22:01.205
