00:56:35.700 --> 00:56:42.480
this also converges to 0, plus--

00:56:42.480 --> 00:56:43.650
how did we define I?

00:56:43.650 --> 00:56:47.190
It was defined as the limit of
the Riemann sums corresponding

00:56:47.190 --> 00:56:49.710
to this first fixed partition.

00:56:49.710 --> 00:56:52.350
And therefore, this
thing in absolute value

00:56:52.350 --> 00:56:59.130
converges to 0 as r
convergence is to infinity.

00:56:59.130 --> 00:57:04.080
All right, so the absolute
value of this thing,

00:57:04.080 --> 00:57:07.950
this Riemann sum, minus I is
bounded by something converging

00:57:07.950 --> 00:57:11.160
to 0 as r goes to infinity.

00:57:11.160 --> 00:57:19.900
And therefore, by
the squeeze theorem,

00:57:19.900 --> 00:57:23.595
we conclude that the limit
as r goes to infinity of s--

00:57:33.220 --> 00:57:37.510
so in other words, no matter
what sequence of partitions

00:57:37.510 --> 00:57:41.000
we take, with norms
converging to 0,

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:45.987
the Riemann sums converge
to this same number I.

00:57:45.987 --> 00:57:47.320
And that's the end of the proof.

00:57:55.000 --> 00:57:57.685
OK.

00:57:57.685 --> 00:57:59.580
It took a lot of
work to do this.

00:57:59.580 --> 00:58:01.250
This is the work
of Raymond, so--

00:58:03.800 --> 00:58:11.165
who was one of the greatest
mathematicians of all time.

00:58:14.440 --> 00:58:17.020
Weierstrass was definitely
one of the greatest analysts

00:58:17.020 --> 00:58:17.590
of all time.

00:58:17.590 --> 00:58:20.380
Riemann, just as a
mathematician in general,

00:58:20.380 --> 00:58:22.795
was one of the
greatest of all time.

00:58:25.636 --> 00:58:27.390
He not only did analysis--

00:58:30.360 --> 00:58:35.170
he applied analysis
to number theory.

00:58:35.170 --> 00:58:38.060
This is the content of the
famous Riemann hypothesis,

00:58:38.060 --> 00:58:40.750
which maybe you've
heard about, which

00:58:40.750 --> 00:58:43.740
is worth a million dollars--

00:58:43.740 --> 00:58:48.520
says something about the zeros
of a certain function, which

00:58:48.520 --> 00:58:52.190
then gives you information
about prime numbers.

00:58:52.190 --> 00:58:56.200
And he also had
deep contributions

00:58:56.200 --> 00:58:59.040
to the foundations of geometry--

00:58:59.040 --> 00:59:01.710
or I should say the foundations
of differential geometry--

00:59:05.040 --> 00:59:11.820
but truly some deep
stuff going on.

00:59:11.820 --> 00:59:15.900
All right, so now we have this
notion of a "remand integral.

00:59:15.900 --> 00:59:21.000
It's this no integral f of
x, which has this property.

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:22.960
No matter what
sequence of partitions

00:59:22.960 --> 00:59:26.280
I take, with norms
converging to 0,

00:59:26.280 --> 00:59:33.070
the partial sums
converge to this number.

00:59:33.070 --> 00:59:34.800
So I'm often going to denote--

00:59:34.800 --> 00:59:43.685
so if you like, this is some
alternative notation I'll use.

00:59:51.770 --> 00:59:55.040
Instead of writing f
of x dx, I may just

00:59:55.040 --> 01:00:00.030
write integral a, b, f.

01:00:00.030 --> 01:00:07.650
So this definition of the
Riemann integral looks

01:00:07.650 --> 01:00:10.440
terrifying if you want to
actually try and compute it.

01:00:10.440 --> 01:00:11.220
And it is.

01:00:11.220 --> 01:00:14.490
So that's the miracle of
the fundamental theorem

01:00:14.490 --> 01:00:17.310
of calculus is that it gives
us a way to compute it.

01:00:17.310 --> 01:00:20.370
And that's why I'm not doing
any examples of computing it

01:00:20.370 --> 01:00:21.300
right now.

01:00:21.300 --> 01:00:27.790
But we can still learn about
some properties of the Riemann

01:00:27.790 --> 01:00:32.280
integral without that to start.

01:00:32.280 --> 01:00:39.280
So now we're moving on to some
properties of the integral.

01:00:41.830 --> 01:00:44.620
And the first is that it--

01:00:44.620 --> 01:00:47.740
so this is a limiting process,
but this limiting process

01:00:47.740 --> 01:00:49.450
is linear in f.

01:00:49.450 --> 01:00:54.370
If I look at Riemann sums
of, let's say, f plus g,

01:00:54.370 --> 01:00:58.960
that's equal to the Riemann sum
of f plus the Riemann sum of g.

01:00:58.960 --> 01:01:03.904
And therefore, since
integration is a limit of this--

01:01:03.904 --> 01:01:06.940
of Riemann sums,
then integration

01:01:06.940 --> 01:01:08.650
should also be linear as well.

01:01:08.650 --> 01:01:17.530
And that's the first
theorem is the linearity

01:01:17.530 --> 01:01:21.820
of the Riemann sum,
Riemann integration--

01:01:21.820 --> 01:01:25.240
f and g are a, b.

01:01:32.080 --> 01:01:41.290
And alpha is in R.

01:01:41.290 --> 01:01:46.270
So first off, alpha f plus
g-- that's going to be--

01:01:46.270 --> 01:01:48.310
so that should not be in a, b.

01:01:48.310 --> 01:01:50.980
This should be a continuous--

01:01:50.980 --> 01:01:52.600
it's the end of a long day, OK?

01:01:52.600 --> 01:01:58.140
So sorry if I'm losing a little
steam here towards the end.

01:01:58.140 --> 01:02:02.567
Anyways, alpha f plus g,
if f and g are continuous--

01:02:02.567 --> 01:02:04.150
this is a continuous
function as well,

01:02:04.150 --> 01:02:07.110
so its integral is meaningful.

01:02:07.110 --> 01:02:11.910
And its integral is equal to
alpha times the integral f

01:02:11.910 --> 01:02:17.030
plus the integral of g.

01:02:17.030 --> 01:02:17.530
OK?

01:02:24.960 --> 01:02:25.843
So what's the proof?

01:02:25.843 --> 01:02:27.510
The proof is basically
what I said right

01:02:27.510 --> 01:02:32.760
before I stated the theorem,
that Riemann sums are

01:02:32.760 --> 01:02:34.020
linear in the function.

01:02:38.910 --> 01:02:42.102
And then we just take a limit.

01:02:42.102 --> 01:02:58.130
Let's take a sequence
of tagged partitions

01:02:58.130 --> 01:03:05.650
with norms converting to
0 as r goes to infinity.

01:03:12.030 --> 01:03:18.790
Then, if I look at the
Riemann sum associated

01:03:18.790 --> 01:03:27.790
to alpha f plus g, it is easy to
see from the definition, right?

01:03:27.790 --> 01:03:33.260
This is a sum from k
equals 1 to [? in-- ?]

01:03:33.260 --> 01:03:35.480
so this is easy to
see that this is

01:03:35.480 --> 01:03:38.930
equal to alpha times
the Riemann some

01:03:38.930 --> 01:03:55.122
associated to f plus that guy.

01:03:55.122 --> 01:03:56.330
And now I just take a limit--

01:03:59.360 --> 01:04:04.190
so take the limit as
r goes to infinity.

01:04:04.190 --> 01:04:10.460
The left-hand side converges
to the Riemann integral

01:04:10.460 --> 01:04:12.680
of alpha f plus g.

01:04:12.680 --> 01:04:16.010
The limit as r goes to
infinity converges to--

01:04:16.010 --> 01:04:22.250
because we know limits
respect linear operations,

01:04:22.250 --> 01:04:23.870
the limit of the
right-hand side is

01:04:23.870 --> 01:04:27.260
going to be alpha times
the limit plus the limit.

01:04:27.260 --> 01:04:31.630
And therefore, this is equal
to alpha times integral a, b,

01:04:31.630 --> 01:04:35.937
f plus integral a, b, g.

01:04:39.600 --> 01:04:41.570
OK.

01:04:41.570 --> 01:04:47.090
So like differentiation,
it's also

01:04:47.090 --> 01:04:51.080
what one would call
a linear operator.

01:04:51.080 --> 01:04:53.540
It takes a function and
spits something out,

01:04:53.540 --> 01:04:55.565
but does it in a linear way.

01:04:55.565 --> 01:05:02.850
So for us, it takes
a continuous function

01:05:02.850 --> 01:05:06.570
and spits out a real
number in a linear way.

01:05:06.570 --> 01:05:08.490
The integral of
alpha f plus g is

01:05:08.490 --> 01:05:10.410
equal to alpha times f plus g.

01:05:10.410 --> 01:05:13.870
Just like differentiation, the
derivative of alpha f plus g

01:05:13.870 --> 01:05:15.990
if everything's
differentiable, is

01:05:15.990 --> 01:05:18.570
equal to alpha times
the derivative of f

01:05:18.570 --> 01:05:21.810
plus the derivative of g.

01:05:21.810 --> 01:05:24.600
But Riemann integration,
the Riemann integral,

01:05:24.600 --> 01:05:32.075
or integration in general,
is in some sense--

01:05:35.260 --> 01:05:36.940
I don't want to say
it's not miraculous.

01:05:36.940 --> 01:05:39.340
It still is a bit
of a miracle that it

01:05:39.340 --> 01:05:42.500
exists for all
continuous functions,

01:05:42.500 --> 01:05:45.610
but it's not as
destructive an operator

01:05:45.610 --> 01:05:48.610
as taking the
derivative, if you take

01:05:48.610 --> 01:05:52.660
as your baseline
continuous functions.

01:05:52.660 --> 01:05:58.380
Last lecture we constructed
a continuous function which

01:05:58.380 --> 01:06:01.950
is differentiable nowhere.

01:06:01.950 --> 01:06:06.660
So with differentiation, you
can take a continuous function

01:06:06.660 --> 01:06:09.950
and not be able to take
its derivative anywhere.

01:06:09.950 --> 01:06:11.930
Well, with integration,
if you start off

01:06:11.930 --> 01:06:15.600
with a continuous function, you
can always take it's integral.

01:06:15.600 --> 01:06:22.950
So somehow integration is a
much more smoother process

01:06:22.950 --> 01:06:24.860
than differentiation.

01:06:24.860 --> 01:06:28.000
All right, so I think
we'll stop there.

